*Ktpgh4XIcwgOB5_c 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/0*Ktpgh4XIcwgOB5_c 1400w"/><img alt="" loading="lazy" role="presentation" src="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:700/0*Ktpgh4XIcwgOB5_c"></picture></div><br></div></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><h4 class="mbr-section-subtitle mbr-fonts-style mb-4 display-5">Previous Works</h4></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Reviewing last year’s projects we saw a project exploring many of the topics we learned in class and applying those to the problem of stock prediction. We wanted to validate the results of this team and optimize where we could as well as extend the project to the emerging field of GANs networks. We chose to explore GANs over the more common research of LSTMs as the next level of predictors after regressors, mostly because of experience overlap and secondly as for the challenge of exploring less researched areas on the fringe of emerging works.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><h4 class="mbr-section-subtitle mbr-fonts-style mb-4 display-5">The Dataset</h4></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">In formulating our project we explored the kaggle competitions and saw as the head of hot new competitions with the largest prize pool, the task of predicting on the JPX market. Yet we avoided participating in this competition as we felt the competition was poorly managed and the dataset was less explored, meaning we would be on our own if we encountered problems. The competition would be open for a matter of months and the leaderboard is populated with people that managed to cheese their scores by finding and fitting on the test dataset, using account submission limit subversion, and generally overfitting their models. With this in mind we decided to score ourselves using a common metric and instead predict on a limited subset of high performing NASDAQ stocks. This would allow us to really tune our results and achieve higher potential performance without worrying about being overly general. This is a common practice at brokerage firms everywhere, where a limited set of stocks are utilized. If the stock is unmentioned in results, the target testing stock was Apple stock.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><h4 class="mbr-section-subtitle mbr-fonts-style mb-4 display-5">What Frameworks are to be Explored</h4></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">We wanted to explore some of the successes of the previous year so that we could have some context to our final results. We will be implementing the same preprocessing methods and scoring metrics for all models to maintain consistency. We will start with a baseline model of a linear regression expected to have poor performance. With this as a minimum viable baseline we then want to replicate the process the group describes for their best model. This means optimizing an XGBoost model and a CAT boost model, then making a stacked ensemble of these two. Our goal is to achieve a higher performance than the best model, and if the work is extremely successful to match or beat real investment strategies. A successful project focuses on exploring the GANs solution so a high performance isn’t a strict requirement of the success of our project, but it will give meaning and weight to our results.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><h4 class="mbr-section-subtitle mbr-fonts-style mb-4 display-5">Evaluation Metric</h4></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">The dataset will be split into past training data and recent testing data, where all extracted and engineered features maintain this split. This will ensure we can validate our initial training results on unseen data. We will be using the Sharpe Ratio which is almost universally the scoring metric used in ML and human investment strategy scoring. The Sharpe ratio was developed by Nobel laureate William F. Sharpe and is used to help investors understand the return of an investment compared to its risk. The ratio is the average return earned in excess of the risk-free rate per unit of volatility or total risk. Volatility is a measure of the price fluctuations of an asset or portfolio. The Sharpe ratio adjusts a portfolio’s past performance, or expected future performance, for the excess risk that was taken by the investor. A high Sharpe ratio is good when compared to similar portfolios or funds with lower returns. The Sharpe ratio has several weaknesses, including an assumption that investment returns are normally distributed.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><h4 class="mbr-section-subtitle mbr-fonts-style mb-4 display-5">Data Preprocessing and Feature Engineering</h4></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">In the realm of technical analysis in finance, a technical indicator refers to a mathematical calculation or pattern signal based on the historic price, volume, or open interest of a security or contract that attempts to forecast financial market direction. For a data scientist this is known as feature engineering. For this project, the top technical indicators as proposed by a field of experts, were taken as features for our networks. Seven day and twenty one day moving averages, exponential moving average, log momentum, Bollinger bands and MACD were all calculated and extracted as features using python libraries. A Fourier transform is a common methodology of reforming your data in a way such that statistical anomalies in your data can be suppressed and has been shown to allow for GRUs (utilized in our GANs model) to learn more robust patterns.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="image3 cid-tt612oXwA9" id="image3-5" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
