*jPxFChbX_yed9m8b 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/0*jPxFChbX_yed9m8b 1400w"/><img alt="" loading="lazy" role="presentation" src="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:700/0*jPxFChbX_yed9m8b"></picture></div><p class="mbr-description mbr-fonts-style mt-2 align-center display-12 text-muted" style="font-size:12px;">*Note that this is a testing set, mislabeled as training. The original result was lost and could not be corrected.*</p><br></div></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Now does this mean that the model does not work? Not exactly, and here is potentially why. In a review of other similar works, normally using regressors or LSTMs, a few papers mention the COVID period as an anomaly in the data that is reasonably unprecedented. This is a simplistic explanation with a similarly simple solution of excluding the anomalous period that I believe to just be masking an issue, so I will not be taking this approach.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">What if instead what is happening here is that the future data is unbelievable to the current model as it exceeds the bounds of anything it has ever seen before. If you observe the prices of training and then of testing what you see is that the price had never before exceeded around 40USD. With this context and then perhaps the tail end of training where high price is followed by a rebounding price drop, maybe the results have some measure of believability. Yet the fact remains that this is a negative result. You could train the model everytime new data becomes available but that is undesirable. Instead we consider if we can change the data format such that old and new data are much the same. This could be achieved if we transform the data from USD to % gains or loss as scaled between [-1, 1].</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">So we set out to see if this <strong>hypothesis </strong>and correction yielded a better result and achieved the following result:</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="image3 cid-tt612oXwA9" id="image3-5" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-12 col-lg-9">
                <div class="image-wrapper"><div class="image_style" style="width:96%;"><picture><source sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/0*IKliAYGlQpoVRbXs 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/0*IKliAYGlQpoVRbXs 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/0*IKliAYGlQpoVRbXs 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/0*IKliAYGlQpoVRbXs 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/0*IKliAYGlQpoVRbXs 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/0*IKliAYGlQpoVRbXs 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/0*IKliAYGlQpoVRbXs 1400w" type="image/webp"/><source data-testid="og" sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/0*IKliAYGlQpoVRbXs 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/0*IKliAYGlQpoVRbXs 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/0*IKliAYGlQpoVRbXs 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/0*IKliAYGlQpoVRbXs 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/0*IKliAYGlQpoVRbXs 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/0